---
title: "Testing a Language"
author: bad-antics
date: 2026-04-06
abstract: We test Lateralus itself using a combination of 1976 tests, snapshot testing, property-based testing, and a robust CI pipeline.

---

## Our Testing Strategy

We take testing seriously. After all, if we can't trust our own code, how can we expect users to trust ours? Our testing strategy is built around three pillars: exhaustive testing, incremental testing, and continuous integration.

### Exhaustive Testing

Exhaustive testing involves writing a large number of unit tests that cover every possible scenario. This can be a daunting task, but it ensures that we catch any bugs or edge cases that might slip through the cracks. We use a mix of hand-written tests and automated tools like `ltlml-test` to make this process more efficient.

// Example of an exhaustive test
fn example(x: int) -> bool {
    // Test that x is even
    return x % 2 == 0;
}

### Incremental Testing

Incremental testing involves building new features incrementally, while still maintaining a stable base of tests. This approach allows us to test small pieces of code in isolation, which makes it easier to identify and fix issues.

// Example of incremental testing
fn example_incremental() -> int {
    // Use a library function to perform some calculation
    let result = my_library_function(42);
    return result * 2;
}

### Continuous Integration

Continuous integration (CI) involves integrating our code into a shared repository, where it can be automatically tested and built on every push. This ensures that our code is always up-to-date and that any regressions are caught quickly.

// Example of CI pipeline
fn example_ci() -> bool {
    // Perform some checks before accepting the pull request
    if !my_test_passed() {
        return false;
    }
    return true;
}

## Our CI Pipeline

Our CI pipeline is built around `ltlml-test`, which provides a robust set of tools for testing Lateralus code. The pipeline consists of three stages: build, test, and deploy. During the build stage, we compile our code and generate documentation. In the test stage, we run all of our unit tests and sanity checks. Finally, during the deploy stage, we package up our code and deploy it to production.

